The paper discusses a method for speeding up distributed computing using coding techniques. This falls under the category of Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC). The paper also discusses the use of combinatorial structures and their interpretation, which suggests a possible connection to Information Theory (cs.IT). The use of partitioning and shuffling of data suggests a connection to Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS). The use of coded transmission suggests a connection to Signal Processing (cs.SI). Finally, the use of distributed computing frameworks such as MapReduce suggests a connection to Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI).
